of the following is the most appropriate professional response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide information about alternative medical treatments only","Document that the patient is non-compliant and arrange psychiatric review","Respect the patient\u0027s informed decision while maintaining supportive care","Explain that the hospital cannot accept liability for complications","Document that all reasonable attempts at persuasion have failed"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erespect the patient\u0027s informed decision while maintaining supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E. This upholds the fundamental principle of patient autonomy while ensuring ongoing medical care remains available. The patient has demonstrated capacity to make decisions and has been properly informed of the risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses violate professional principles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide information about alternative medical treatments only\u003C/strong\u003E - This response abandons the duty of care by failing to maintain supportive care options\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocument that the patient is non-compliant and arrange psychiatric review\u003C/strong\u003E - This response stigmatises the patient\u0027s choice and incorrectly assumes that declining recommended treatment indicates psychiatric illness\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplain that the hospital cannot accept liability for complications\u003C/strong\u003E - This is defensive medicine that prioritises institutional protection over patient care\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocument that all reasonable attempts at persuasion have failed\u003C/strong\u003E - This implies coercion was appropriate and fails to respect patient autonomy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers must maintain professional respect for patient choices even when these differ from medical recommendations, while continuing to provide appropriate care within the scope of what the patient accepts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respect for patient autonomy means supporting informed decision-making even when patients decline recommended treatments.","Medical professionals must maintain respectful communication and behaviour regardless of personal beliefs or disagreements.","Cultural safety requires healthcare providers to acknowledge and respect diverse cultural beliefs and practices."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Ajluni V. Respecting autonomy: Prioritizing patient-centered care and decision-making capacity for stronger doctor-patient relationships. J Family Med Prim Care. 2023 Aug;12(8):1752-1753. doi: 10.4103/jfmpc.jfmpc_712_23. Epub 2023 Aug 29. PMID: 37767408; PMCID: PMC10521844. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10521844/","Rodriguez-Osorio CA, Dominguez-Cherit G. Medical decision making: paternalism versus patient-centered (autonomous) care. Curr Opin Crit Care. 2008 Dec;14(6):708-13. doi: 10.1097/MCC.0b013e328315a611. PMID: 19005314. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19005314/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T13:22:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T13:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11584"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79715